│ The logic in `buildTreeRec` gathers operands from a set of instructions to form a new   │
│ candidate group. While doing so, it fails to filter out terminator instructions. When   │
│ this group containing the `invoke` instruction is passed to the `tryScheduleBundle`     │
│ function, the scheduler is set up for the block of the first instruction in the group.  │
│ When it later encounters the `invoke` instruction, which is a terminator, the           │
│ scheduling logic fails, leading to the crash.                                           │
│                                                                                         │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                           │
│                                                                                         │
│ The correct fix is to prevent terminator instructions from ever being considered as     │
│ part of a vectorization candidate bundle. This can be achieved by adding a check in the │
│ operand-gathering loop within the `buildTreeRec` function.                              │
│                                                                                         │
│ **File**: `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp`                             │
│                                                                                         │
│ **Edit Point**: Insert the following code at line 11685, just before an operand is      │
│ added to the `Operands` list.                                                           │
│                                                                                         │
│ ```cpp                                                                                  │
│       if (auto *OpI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Op)) {                                      │
│         if (OpI->isTerminator())                                                        │
│           continue;                                                                     │
│       }                                                                                 │
│ ```                                                                                     │
│                                                                                         │
│ This change inspects each potential operand `Op`. If it is an instruction and also a    │
│ terminator, the `continue` statement skips it, preventing it from being added to the    │
│ `Operands` list for further vectorization attempts. This ensures that the scheduler     │
│ will not encounter terminator instructions.                                             │
│                                                                                         │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                                                       │
│                                                                                         │
│ The crash is a direct result of the SLP vectorizer improperly attempting to include a   │
│ terminator instruction in a vectorization bundle. The scheduler is not designed for     │
│ this and fails. The proposed fix addresses the root cause by filtering out terminator   │
│ instructions during the candidate gathering phase in `buildTreeRec`. This is a precise  │
│ and safe correction that prevents the illegal transformation and allows the vectorizer  │
│ to function correctly.                                                                  │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                         │
